Hey, it's the anon who did some reviews several threads ago. I'm responding to request so here it is. Just note, this review is a bit more critical than usual.

Note: (SPOILERS)

>Kind of a review to "Wilderness Hearts" by TheSignalRemains

I should start by saying I only got to chapter 6, and I will say why soon.

Firstly, the story is beautifully written, the prose is good, and I sometimes come back to it when I'm doing my writing. This is especially around the combat scenes, particularly the descriptions of pain and the various sorts. It's visceral, brutal, and brilliant.

But I couldn't get myself into the narrative itself.

Nothing grabbed me about the world, characters, setting or conflict. Nothing came off as unique or narratively interesting. I wasn't really given a reason to care about Jan or Ela, or much to their relationship which I feel develops way too soon. They are introduced, have a sob story, but that's as far as it goes.

The whole enemies to lovers trope is played with, but it doesn't last very long, and feels rushed, and Ela's psychotic episodes don't feel like they added anything to the narrative, which goes on but I don't feel much actually happening. I feel the narrative potential, and them learning to live and get over their history together to form a brighter future is squandered.

Overall, I didn't stop reading because it was bad. I stopped reading because I found it failed to engage me.

To follow on what you said.

>Also SPOILER

Following on from my post >>70132886, the moment Jan and Ela had sex should have been a critical moment in the story, a monument to how their relationship has developed from rivals to proper lovers. But it comes way too soon to have an impact on the reader.

Speaking to any other writefags looking for advice. When it comes to pacing any narrative conflict, it's like sex.

Blowing your load to early leads to disappointment, and the reader feeling dissatisfied the conflict ended so soon. They will want more.

Edging for too long however, the reader will get bored and look elsewhere for satisfaction. The conflict takes too long to resolve, or it deviates, stalls, or prose is written which doesn't add to the story.

Pacing is all about balance.

An apocrine sweat gland (/ËæpÉkrÉn, -ËkraJn, -ËkriËn/; from Greek apo 'away' and krinein 'to separate')[5][6] is composed of a coiled secretory portion located at the junction of the dermis and subcutaneous fat, from which a straight portion inserts and secretes into the infundibular portion of the hair follicle.[7] In humans, apocrine sweat glands are found only in certain locations of the body: the axillae (armpits), areola and nipples of the breast, ear canal, eyelids, wings of the nostril, perineal region, and some parts of the external genitalia.[8] Modified apocrine glands include the ciliary glands (glands of Moll) in the eyelids; the ceruminous glands, which produce ear wax; and the mammary glands, which produce milk.[3] They are distinct from eccrine sweat glands, which cover the whole body.[9]

Most non-primate mammals, however, have apocrine sweat glands over the greater part of their body.[8] Domestic animals such as dogs and cats have apocrine glands at each hair follicle and even in their urinary system, but eccrine glands only in foot pads and snout. Their apocrine glands, like those in humans, produce an odorless, oily, opaque secretion[10] that gains its characteristic odor upon bacterial decomposition.[11] Eccrine glands on their paws increase friction and prevent them from slipping when fleeing from danger.[12]
